Flag officer commanding (FOC) Eastern Naval Command, Rear Admiral David Adeniran, yesterday said the command is keeping track of all vessels coming into Nigeria via the Calabar inland waterways in order to contain the dreaded Coronavirus. Adeniran stated this while answering questions from reporters shortly after the familiarization tour of navy’s facilities under the Eastern Naval command headquarters Calabar by the Senate Committee on Navy lead by Senator George Sekibo. The FOC stressed that the command have facilities like the Falcon Eye and the RMAC which it deploys to monitor all inbound vessels, besides stepping up its corona virus surveillance at all entry points within the Eastern Naval Command. “In terms of entry, the moment we have any information that any ship is coming into Nigeria,  we keep track of that vessel  and we have facilities  like the Falcon Eye and the RMAC where we track the movement of the vessel. “We track the movement of the vessel for the past 30 days and know which waters they have been to and from there we monitor and direct accordingly. Of course, the Navy has the means to reach out to stop the vessel and know where they are coming from. “With that, we are able to advise the port management or the on shore oil facilities accordingly”. Adeniran added that, “like it did during the Ebola Virus episode, the Navy Reference Hospital in Calabar has taken appropriate steps to ensure that whatever issue comes up in this environment they are able to tackle it and also ensure that Convid 19 menace is properly handled at least in its environment.